Practical Lab 1 - Univariate Linear Regression on the California Housing Prices Dataset

Introduction

Goal Of The Report

  • The main objective of this report is to build a univariate linear regression models to predict the median house value for houses in California. Model will evaluate relationship between dependent variable(median house value) and three independent variables(median income, population, and number of household). With this report, we aim to identify which one of the independent variables is the most ideal predictor of median house value which will help in providing valuable insights for decision-making in real estate business.

Obtaining the Data

Source Source: Downloaded from Kaggle California Housing Prices

Descriptions Of 4 Variables based on EDA

  1. median_house_value (Dependent Variable)
  • Meaning: This represents the median house value in various neighborhoods which is measured in dollars.
  • Range: Min: $14,999 Max: $500,000, with the upper limit capped at $500,000, which indicates that higher house values are truncated.
  • Observations: The dataset contains a significant number of neighborhoods where the median house value reaches this upper bound, indicating a potential bias for high-end houses.
  1. median_income (Independent Variable)
  • Meaning: The median income of households within a block group, measured in tens of thousands of dollars.
  • Range: Min: $499.90 (0.5) Max: $150,001 (15.0).
  • Observations: The data shows a wide variability in income levels, and there is a positive correlation between higher median_income and median_house_value. Outliers have been detected and will be removed to avoid skewing the regression results.
  1. population (Independent Variable)
  • Meaning: The population of the block group (i.e., neighborhood or census area). *Range: Min: 3 Max: 35,000 people.
  • Observations: Even though there is a large spread in population exists, there is no strong correlation between population size and median_house_value. Outliers, especially in very high population areas, will be removed to reduce their effect on the analysis.
  1. households (Independent Variable)
  • Meaning: The number of households within each block group.
  • Range: Min: 1 Max: 6,000.
  • Observations: Similar to population, the number of households shows no significant linear relationship with house values. There is a clusters of data points around lower numbers of households, and outliers with exceptionally large numbers of households will be removed to ensure model reliability.

Data Preprocessing

  • Filtering out records capped at median_house_value = 500001 because they can limit the predictive ability of the model
In[50]:
#Removing rows where median_house_value is capped
data = data[data['median_house_value'] < 500001]
  • Removing outliers for all the independent variables using 1.5 IQR to increase the accuracy of the model
In[51]:
def remove_outliers(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return df[(df[column] >= lower_bound) & (df[column] <= upper_bound)]
In[52]:
#Remove outliers for median_income
data = remove_outliers(data, 'median_income')

#Remove outliers for population
data = remove_outliers(data, 'population')

#Remove outliers for households
data = remove_outliers(data, 'households')

Define The Models

  • Creating Linear Regression objects for all 3 models
In[58]:
model_income = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model_population = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model_households = linear_model.LinearRegression()
In[59]:
#Fitting the models
model_income.fit(X=train[["median_income"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])
model_population.fit(X=train[["population"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])
model_households.fit(X=train[["households"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])

In[60]:
#Making predictions
y_pred_income = model_income.predict(test[["median_income"]])
y_pred_population = model_population.predict(test[["population"]])
y_pred_households = model_households.predict(test[["households"]])
In[61]:
#Calculating MSE and MAE for each model
mse_income = mean_squared_error(test["median_house_value"], y_pred_income)
mae_income = mean_absolute_error(test["median_house_value"], y_pred_income)

mse_population = mean_squared_error(test["median_house_value"], y_pred_population)
mae_population = mean_absolute_error(test["median_house_value"], y_pred_population)

mse_households = mean_squared_error(test["median_house_value"], y_pred_households)
mae_households = mean_absolute_error(test["median_house_value"], y_pred_households)
In[62]:
#Extracting intercepts and slopes
intercept_income = model_income.intercept_
slope_income = model_income.coef_[0]

intercept_population = model_population.intercept_
slope_population = model_population.coef_[0]

intercept_households = model_households.intercept_
slope_households = model_households.coef_[0]

Model Interpretation:

  1. Median Income Model:
  • Intercept: 43,307.24, which means when the median_income is 0, the predicted median_house_value is approx. $43,307.
  • Slope: 39,849.54, suggesting that for each 1 unit increase in median_income (1 unit = 10,000$), the median_house_value increases by $39,849.
  • MSE and MAE: This model has the lowest MSE which is 5.69e+09 and MAE, 59,511, indicating that it provides the most accurate predictions out of the three models.
  1. Population Model:
  • Intercept: 187,936.29, indicating that the predicted median_house_value is around $187,936 when the population is 0.
  • Slope: -3.69, shows that for every 1 person increase in population, the median_house_value decreases by $3.69.
  • MSE and MAE: This model has the highest MSE (1.06e+10) and MAE (84,609), that proves it performs poorly in predicting house prices based on population.
  1. Number of Households Model:
  • Intercept: 159,501.15, that means when the number of households is 0, the predicted median_house_value is approx. $159,501.
  • Slope: 57.85, showing that for every 1 household increase, the median_house_value increases by about $57.85.
  • MSE and MAE: This model has a bit better performance than the population model but it is still less accurate than the median income model.

Plotting Regression Line with Scatter Data

In[64]:
def plot_regression_with_metrics(train_data, test_data, train_pred, test_pred, title, intercept, slope, mse, mae, x_var, y_var):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    
    #Scatter plot for the training data
    sns.scatterplot(x=x_var, y=y_var, data=train_data, color="blue", label="Train Data")
    plt.plot(train_data[[x_var]], train_pred, color="black", linewidth=3, label="Train Regression Line")

    #Scatter plot for the testing data
    sns.scatterplot(x=x_var, y=y_var, data=test_data, color="orange", label="Test Data")
    plt.plot(test_data[[x_var]], test_pred, color="red", linewidth=3, label="Test Regression Line")

    #Title and labels
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(x_var)
    plt.ylabel(y_var)

    intercept = intercept[0] if isinstance(intercept, np.ndarray) else intercept
    slope = slope[0] if isinstance(slope, np.ndarray) else slope

    #Adding text box with model parameters (Intercept, Slope, MSE, MAE)
    textstr = f'Intercept: {intercept:.2f}\nSlope: {slope:.2f}\nMSE: {mse:.2e}\nMAE: {mae:.2f}'
    plt.gca().text(0.05, 0.95, textstr, transform=plt.gca().transAxes,
                   fontsize=12, verticalalignment='top', bbox=dict(boxstyle="round", facecolor='wheat', alpha=0.5))

    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
  • Created this function for regression line with labels and text box with model parameters using Chatgpt.

Conclusion and Insights

The Median income model however is the one that has the best goodness of fit while predicting the price of the houses since it recorded lower MSE and MAE as opposed to Population and Number of Households models that have weak association and higher error metrics leading to poor prediction accuracy.

Model Comparison (Goodness-of-Fit):

  • Median Income: This is the best model which possess a high degree of correlation towards the dependent variable and having the least error values (MSE: 5.69e+09, MAE: 59,511) that portrays the strongest linear relationship connection between income and house prices.

  • Population: This was rather disappointing as the model performed the worst registering a rather flat or even downward facing curve against the range of variables of house prices (MSE: 1.06e+10, MAE: 84,610) which led to the conclusion that population size is not a useful indicator of house prices.

  • Number of Households: This was a shade better than the population however a very weak predictor (MSE: 1.04e+10, MAE: 83,387) with only the slightest positive slope indicating minimal influences on the prices of houses.

Insights:

  • The Median Income model clearly demonstrates that income levels are an obvious influencer of house prices, whereas Population and Number of Households might be more complex in their modeling or might need more features to help explain their effect on housing prices.
